"""
MKT Original Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 22–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1samuel-22-24.py

Ch 22: Cave of Adullam; David's distressed followers; Doeg betrays Nob; massacre of priests.
Ch 23: David delivers Keilah; ephod oracle; Jonathan's covenant visit; wilderness flight.
Ch 24: David spares Saul in the cave at En-gedi; robe corner; covenant argument.

Key term decisions:
- YHWH throughout (not LORD)
- nāgîd: prince/leader (distinct from melek)
- ʾānan: inquired/sought oracle (technical term for ephod consultation)
- māšîaḥ / māšaḥ: anointed/anointed one (not "the LORD's anointed" — YHWH's anointed)
- kānāp: corner/wing (of robe — the covenant significance of garment corner)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(type_, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(type_, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

ORIG = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>David escapes to the cave of Adullam (<em>mĕʿāraṯ ʿăḏullām</em>). Adullam was in the Shephelah foothills of Judah — rugged terrain offering natural fortress geography. The cave became David's first base of operations during his years as a fugitive. The Psalms associated with this period (Pss 34, 57, 142) reflect the emotional register of this flight: fear, trust, praise amid extremity. His brothers and father's household come to him — the very family Samuel bypassed when anointing the youngest son is now drawn to him in crisis.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Three classes of men gather to David: those in distress (<em>māṣôq</em>), those in debt (<em>nōšeh</em>), and those bitter of soul (<em>mar nepeš</em>). The 400-man band that forms around David is the social underside of Saul's court economy — those whose lives are not working within the existing power structure. This gathering has sociological as well as theological significance: YHWH's anointed draws the marginalized, not the established. The Psalms of lament that emerge from this period encode the spirituality of those who have lost standing.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David takes his father and mother to the king of Moab at Mizpah, asking that they stay under the Moabite king's protection while David waits to see what God will do. The Moab connection is unexpected until one remembers that David's great-grandmother was Ruth the Moabitess. David's appeal to Moab is a kinship appeal — he has family claim on Moabite protection. This is also an act of filial piety: David's flight does not include abandoning his aged parents to the hazards of cave life.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David's parents stay with the king of Moab as long as David is in the stronghold. <em>Hammĕṣûḏāh</em> (the stronghold) is the same term used for Masada — a fortified high place. David moves between the cave of Adullam and various mountain strongholds throughout chs 22-26. The protection of parents during the son's military campaign is a recurring narrative detail that characterizes David's household responsibility even in extremity.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The prophet Gad — who will later serve as David's court prophet (2 Sam 24:11) and co-author of records (1 Chr 29:29) — appears here for the first time, instructing David: 'Do not remain in the stronghold; go into the land of Judah.' The divine word through a prophet redirects David back into the territory of his own tribe. This is both strategically and theologically significant: David must be in Judah, in covenant territory, rather than in the security of a cave. Gad's appearance establishes that David continues to receive prophetic guidance throughout the fugitive years.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Saul hears that David and his men have been discovered. He sits at Gibeah under the tamarisk tree on the hill, spear in hand, surrounded by his servants. The tamarisk tree (<em>ʾešel</em>) is a specific detail — possibly a throne-tree, the kind under which kings held court (cf. 1 Sam 31:13 where Saul is buried under the tamarisk). The spear in Saul's hand is a recurring image: it is the weapon he twice hurled at David (18:11; 19:10) and at Jonathan (20:33). The symbol of power has become a symbol of paranoia.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul addresses his Benjaminite servants: 'Will the son of Jesse give every one of you fields and vineyards? Will he make you all commanders of thousands and commanders of hundreds?' Saul's appeal is explicitly tribal and economic: he frames David's potential kingship as a threat to Benjaminite patronage networks. The language of fields, vineyards, and military ranks recalls Samuel's warning about royal extraction (8:14-16). Saul wields the fear of losing what the king gives as a loyalty mechanism.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Saul's paranoid accusation: 'that all of you have conspired against me; that none of you discloses to me when my son makes a league with the son of Jesse.' He uses the covenant vocabulary of Jonathan and David's relationship (<em>kāraṯ bərît</em>, make a covenant) but frames it as treason. Saul's inability to distinguish covenant friendship from political conspiracy is a symptom of the evil spirit that has replaced the Spirit of YHWH. His claim that 'none of you is sorry for me' (<em>ḥālaṯ ʿālay</em>) reflects the isolation of a man who has rejected the bonds that would make loyalty voluntary.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Doeg the Edomite, the man who 'was detained before YHWH' at the Nob sanctuary (21:7), now speaks: 'I saw the son of Jesse coming to Nob, to Ahimelech son of Ahitub.' The informer is an Edomite — a foreigner in Saul's service, and the only one willing to exploit Ahimelech's hospitality. Doeg's identity as an Edomite gives him no stake in Israelite covenant relationships; he is the outsider who sees opportunity in Saul's paranoia. Psalm 52 is attributed to this moment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Doeg reports that Ahimelech inquired of YHWH for David, gave him provisions, and gave him the sword of Goliath. The three acts — oracle consultation, bread, weapon — are precisely what was needed for a fugitive on a mission. The sword of Goliath kept at the sanctuary as a trophy now becomes evidence of collusion. Doeg's testimony is selective: he does not mention Ahimelech's question about David's status (21:2) or his apparent belief that David was on a royal mission.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul summons Ahimelech and all his father's house — the entire priestly community of Nob — to appear before him. The summoning of the full priestly family indicates Saul intends a judgment against the whole community, not just the individual. Nob was the sanctuary city that housed the displaced priesthood after Shiloh's destruction; it was the institutional home of the Elide priestly line that Samuel had already pronounced under judgment (2:31-36).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Saul addresses Ahimelech: 'Listen now, son of Ahitub.' The formal address by patronymic signals judicial procedure. Ahimelech answers: 'Here I am, my lord.' His posture throughout the interrogation is calm and transparent — he does not attempt to deny or obscure what happened, because he acted in good faith.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Saul's accusation: 'Why have you conspired against me, you and the son of Jesse, by giving him bread and a sword and by inquiring of God for him, so that he has rebelled against me and lies in wait for me?' Saul reframes every act of priestly hospitality as conspiracy and reframes David's flight as armed rebellion. The inversion is complete: the one pursued becomes the pursuer, the priestly act of service becomes treason.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ahimelech's defense is direct: 'Who among all your servants is as faithful as David? He is the king's son-in-law, and the captain of your bodyguard, and honored in your house.' Ahimelech argues from David's known status — he had every reason to believe David was on legitimate royal business. The defense appeals to David's demonstrated covenant loyalty, his family ties to the king, and his military rank. All of these were true — and all of them are what Saul had already dismantled through jealousy.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Was it the first time I inquired of God for him? By no means! Let not the king impute anything to his servant or to all the house of my father, for your servant has known nothing of all this, little or great.' Ahimelech insists on his ignorance of any political dimension. His defense is factually strong: he had consulted YHWH for David before (on legitimate royal missions) and had no reason to suspect a change in David's status. The phrase 'little or great' (<em>qāṭān wəgāḏôl</em>) means 'in any measure whatsoever' — a comprehensive denial.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Saul pronounces the death sentence: 'You shall surely die, Ahimelech, you and all your father's house.' The judgment is collective — the entire priestly family is condemned for one man's hospitality, rendered in good faith, to the king's own son-in-law. The injustice is stark: no counter-evidence is allowed, no witnesses are called, no process is observed. Saul's paranoia has wholly displaced the judicial function of kingship.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul commands his guards to kill the priests of YHWH. But none of his servants will stretch out their hand to strike the priests of YHWH — <em>kî lōʾ ʾāḇû yāḏām liślōaḥ lipgôaʿ bəḵōhănê YHWH</em>. The refusal of Saul's own Israelite soldiers is the narrative's moral landmark: even the king's sworn servants recognize a line they will not cross. The inviolability of YHWH's priests was so fundamental that the soldiers' conscience overrides direct royal command. Saul's order is a line Israel will not follow.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Saul turns to Doeg: 'You turn and strike the priests.' Doeg the Edomite turns and strikes the priests — 85 men who wore the linen ephod. The specific number and the detail of the priestly vestment (<em>ʾēpôḏ bāḏ</em>) makes this an official priestly execution — these were consecrated servants killed in their sacred office. Doeg has no scruple about killing the priests of a covenant he does not share. The Edomite does what Israel's soldiers refused to do.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Doeg strikes Nob, the city of priests, with the sword — men and women, children and infants, oxen, donkeys, and sheep — the total destruction formula of <em>ḥērem</em> (ban). The slaughter of Nob is the inversion of the holy war command: the <em>ḥērem</em> was prescribed against Canaanite idolaters and the Amalekites, but Saul applied it to the city of YHWH's own priests. The Agag chapter (15:7-9) showed Saul unwilling to apply <em>ḥērem</em> to the commanded target; here he applies it to the covenant people themselves. The irony is the narrator's indictment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>One son of Ahimelech son of Ahitub escapes: Abiathar, who flees to David. The survival of Abiathar fulfills the prophecy of 2:33 that 'all the increase of your house shall die by the sword of men' yet 'one man shall not be cut off from my altar.' Abiathar is the remnant of the Elide priestly line — the single survivor who carries the priestly tradition and the ephod into David's camp.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abiathar reports to David that Saul has killed the priests of YHWH. The news is not surprising to David — his foreknowledge of Doeg's danger was already expressed in 21:7. But learning it has happened is different from suspecting it might. The priestly massacre becomes the event that binds Abiathar and David together for the rest of David's life; Abiathar will remain David's priest until Adonijah's ill-fated bid (1 Kings 2:26-27).</p>",
    "22": "<p>David says to Abiathar: 'I knew on that day, when Doeg the Edomite was there, that he would surely tell Saul. I have brought about the death of all the persons of your father's house.' David's confession is remarkable: he accepts moral responsibility for the massacre without having intended it. His knowledge of Doeg's presence, combined with his choice to involve Ahimelech anyway, makes him a causal agent. David does not deflect the weight of this onto Saul alone.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Stay with me; do not be afraid, for he who seeks your life seeks my life. With me you shall be in safekeeping.' David's protection-promise to Abiathar is covenant language: he takes the priest under his personal protection in full acknowledgment of his own partial responsibility. The phrase 'with me you shall be safeguarded' (<em>kî mišmeret ʾattāh ʿimmî</em>) uses the language of the sanctuary watch — David becomes Abiathar's refuge. The priest who has lost everything finds covering under the king who lost everything too.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>David is told that the Philistines are fighting against Keilah and raiding the threshing floors. Keilah was a fortified town in the Shephelah southwest of Adullam, in Judahite territory. Raiding threshing floors was a classic harvest-time tactic — grain was the agricultural wealth of the region and threshing floors were exposed sites outside the city walls. David is being drawn into a role as protector of his own tribe.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David inquires of YHWH: 'Shall I go and strike these Philistines?' YHWH says: 'Go, strike the Philistines and save Keilah.' The brief oracle-consultation is technically an ephod inquiry (v6) — the binary yes/no form of the <em>ûrîm wəṯummîm</em>. This is the first of several oracle consultations in ch 23, establishing a pattern: David consults before acting. The contrast with Saul, who acts without consulting (and is later condemned for it in 28:6), is the narrator's quiet theological commentary.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David's men express their fear: 'We are afraid here in Judah; how much more if we go to Keilah against the armies of the Philistines?' The men's reluctance is understandable — they are already hunted fugitives, not a standing army. Their hesitation leads David to consult YHWH a second time (v4), establishing that divine confirmation, not human courage, is the basis for military action.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David inquires of YHWH again. YHWH answers: 'Rise and go down to Keilah, for I will give the Philistines into your hand.' The double oracle confirms the action against the second-guessing of the men. The repetition of consultation is not lack of faith but the narrative's insistence that David acts only on divine authorization. Where Saul acts precipitously (13:9-10) or consults the dead (28:7), David repeatedly consults the living God.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David and his men go to Keilah, fight the Philistines, and strike them with a great blow — also driving off their livestock. The military victory is total and immediate, confirming the oracle. The livestock detail is practical: captured Philistine animals provide food and possibly pack animals for the fugitive band. The victory at Keilah establishes David as a protector of Judahite towns even before he is their king.</p>",
    "6": "<p>When Abiathar fled to David at Keilah, he had the ephod with him. This retrospective note explains the oracle consultations of vv2 and 4: Abiathar's arrival with the ephod gave David access to the binary oracle mechanism that had been at Nob. The ephod (the high-priestly vestment housing the <em>ûrîm wəṯummîm</em> oracle stones) is now in David's camp — and absent from Saul's. This is a significant transfer of covenant-inquiry capacity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul is told David has gone to Keilah and thinks: 'God has sold him into my hand, for he has shut himself in by entering a walled city with gates and bars.' Saul's theological interpretation — 'God has given him to me' — is a misreading of the situation. He assumes the walls that protect Keilah from Philistines will trap David for him. The irony is that Saul is reading providence exactly backwards: what YHWH has used to save Keilah, Saul thinks YHWH is using against David.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Saul summons all the people to war, to go down to Keilah to besiege David and his men. The king who just massacred YHWH's priests is now mobilizing the army to pursue YHWH's anointed. The trajectory of Saul's reign is now clear: the man appointed to protect Israel from its enemies is using Israel's military resources against the man YHWH has designated as his successor.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David knows that Saul is plotting evil against him and says to Abiathar the priest: 'Bring the ephod.' David's knowledge of Saul's planning is not specified — it may be intelligence reports or prophetic awareness — but his response is immediate consultation. The ephod is the proper instrument of decision; David does not act on information alone but seeks divine direction.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David prays: 'YHWH, God of Israel, your servant has heard that Saul seeks to come to Keilah, to destroy the city on my account. Will the leaders of Keilah give me up into his hand? Will Saul come down, as your servant has heard? YHWH God of Israel, please tell your servant.' The prayer frames two binary questions for oracle response: (1) Will the leaders hand David over? (2) Will Saul come? Each requires a yes/no answer from the ephod oracle.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH answers: 'He will come down.' David presses further: 'Will the men of Keilah give me and my men over to Saul?' YHWH says: 'They will give you up.' The answer is uncomfortable: the very city David just saved will surrender him to his pursuer. This is not ingratitude so much as political reality — Keilah cannot withstand Saul's siege on David's behalf. YHWH's oracle is not encouraging; it is honest. David's response is immediate departure.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH's answer that Keilah's leaders would surrender David confirms the necessity of flight. The detail is theologically important: David left Keilah not to save himself from betrayal by ungrateful citizens, but because YHWH told him to. Providence and oracle together direct his movements. He does not wait to see whether the prophecy proves true; the oracle is sufficient authorization for action.</p>",
    "13": "<p>David and his men — now about 600 — leave Keilah and wander wherever they can go. When Saul is told David has escaped from Keilah, he abandons the campaign. The force has grown from 400 (22:2) to 600 — the fugitive band is attracting more recruits even under pressure. 600 is a symbolically significant number in the Hebrew Bible (the size of Saul's fighting force in 13:15 and the original Danite migration in Judg 18:11).</p>",
    "14": "<p>David stays in the wilderness in strongholds and in the hill country of Ziph. Saul hunts for him every day, but God does not give David into his hand. The summary statement — 'God did not give him into his hand' (<em>wəlōʾ-nəḵānô ʾĕlōhîm bəyāḏô</em>) — is the theological verdict on the entire chase. Saul's persistent military resources are overridden by a simple divine restraint. The wilderness strongholds are not David's defense; YHWH's refusal is.</p>",
    "15": "<p>David fears because Saul has come out to seek his life. David is in the wilderness of Ziph at Horesh. The vulnerability is real — Saul's intelligence network is locating David despite the wilderness. Fear is the appropriate human response to a well-resourced enemy; it is also the context in which Jonathan's visit (v16) arrives as YHWH's answer.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jonathan, Saul's son, rises and goes to David at Horesh and strengthens his hand in God (<em>waḥazzeq ʾeṯ-yāḏô bēʾlōhîm</em>). The phrase is theologically precise: Jonathan does not merely encourage David emotionally but strengthens his grip on God — reinforces his trust, his covenant relationship, his faith. This is the last recorded meeting between Jonathan and David. It is the covenant friend's final act before his death at Jezreel (31:2).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jonathan says: 'Do not fear, for the hand of Saul my father shall not find you. You shall be king over Israel, and I shall be next to you.' Jonathan's confession — 'you shall be king' — is more than comforting prediction; it is covenant affirmation of David's divine appointment at cost to himself. Jonathan speaks of his own subordination ('I shall be next to you') without resentment. He has fully embraced that David's kingship displaces the inheritance he would have received as Saul's heir.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Both of them make a covenant before YHWH. Jonathan returns to his house and David remains at Horesh. The covenant renewal at Horesh is the third Jonathan-David covenant (first in 18:3; renewed in 20:16-17; now again here). Each covenant is more costly than the last: this one is made while David is a fugitive and Jonathan is the crown prince who should logically be David's enemy. The covenant's persistence through these conditions is its theological weight.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Ziphites come up to Saul at Gibeah and betray David's location: 'Is David not hiding among us in the strongholds at Horesh, on the hill of Hachilah, which is south of Jeshimon?' The Ziphites are from Judah — they are betraying their own tribesman. The willingness of Judahites to hand David to Saul reflects the political complexity of tribal loyalty: Saul is the king, and the consequences of harboring the king's enemy are severe.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Ziphites offer to deliver David to Saul whenever the king desires. Their initiative is pro-active treachery: they are not responding to a royal demand but volunteering information for political favor. Psalm 54 is headed 'When the Ziphites came and told Saul, David is hiding among us' — the psalm channels David's response to betrayal into worship.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul blesses them: 'May you be blessed by YHWH, for you have had compassion on me.' The irony is acute: Saul invokes YHWH's blessing on the men who are helping him hunt YHWH's anointed. The blessing-formula for informers against the anointed king is self-defeating — YHWH's blessing does not follow acts that oppose YHWH's purposes. Saul's religious language has been completely severed from YHWH's actual will.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Saul instructs the Ziphites to learn David's location with precision: 'Go, make yet more sure. Know and see the place where his foot is, and who has seen him there.' The intelligence operation Saul runs is detailed and methodical. He wants location, cover patterns, and eyewitness confirmation. His persistence contrasts with his earlier inability to sustain military initiatives (13:8-15; 15:9).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'See and learn all the hiding places where he hides, and come back to me with sure information, and I will go with you. And if he is in the land, I will search him out among all the thousands of Judah.' Saul's comprehensive threat — he will search through all Judah's clans — reflects the totalizing logic of his paranoia. His kingdom's resources are now fully redirected toward eliminating a single man who has not raised his hand against Saul.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Ziphites leave ahead of Saul. David and his men are in the wilderness of Maon, in the Arabah to the south of Jeshimon. The wilderness of Maon is in the southern Judean highlands south of Hebron — rugged, semi-arid terrain ideal for concealment. Saul and his men approach on one side of the mountain while David and his men are on the other.</p>",
    "25": "<p>David hears that Saul has come and goes down to the rock in the wilderness of Maon. Saul hears and pursues David into the wilderness of Maon. The mountain becomes a fulcrum: the pursued and the pursuer circling opposite sides, neither able to break through to the other. The geography creates a dramatic near-miss that the narrator prolongs deliberately.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Saul goes on one side of the mountain and David with his men on the other. David is hurrying to escape from Saul. Saul and his men were closing in on David and his men to seize them. The Hebrew here uses the verb <em>yāʾaṭ</em> (surround/encircle) — the tactical maneuver is an encirclement, not just a chase. The trap is almost complete.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A messenger comes to Saul: 'Hurry and come, for the Philistines have raided the land.' The providential timing is exact: the moment of maximum danger for David is the moment YHWH causes a Philistine raid to call Saul away. The external military threat that Israel's king is supposed to address breaks the encirclement. YHWH's rescue comes not through miracle but through the geopolitical pressures that routinely pull kings away from their obsessions.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Saul turns back from pursuing David and goes against the Philistines. This place was called the Rock of Escape (<em>Selaʿ-hammaḥlĕqôṯ</em>) — the Rock of Divisions, or the Rock of Escape — named after the event where the mountain divided pursuer from pursued. Place-name etiologies in Samuel mark the moments of YHWH's dramatic intervention with memorial geography.</p>",
    "29": "<p>David goes up from there and lives in the strongholds of En-gedi. En-gedi — the Spring of the Wild Goat — is a dramatic oasis on the western shore of the Dead Sea, where fresh springs cascade through the rock faces of the Judean wilderness. The strongholds there are nearly inaccessible. David has moved from Adullam to Keilah to Ziph to Maon and now to En-gedi — a trajectory deeper into the wilderness as Saul's pressure increases.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>After Saul returns from pursuing the Philistines, he is told David is in the wilderness of En-gedi. The transition is rapid: the Philistine crisis resolved, Saul immediately resumes the pursuit. The obsession is undiverted. Three thousand chosen men of Israel are deployed specifically against one fugitive — a gross disproportion that the narrative leaves as silent indictment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul takes three thousand chosen men from all Israel and goes to seek David and his men in front of the Rocks of the Wild Goats. The specific terrain — wild goat rocks — is the terrain of En-gedi's cliff faces and caves. The setting is also a theological image: the wild goat (<em>yāʿēl</em>) is the creature of inaccessible heights, living where humans cannot easily go. David has retreated into the wild goat's territory.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Saul comes to the sheep-folds along the way, where there was a cave, and goes in to relieve himself. David and his men are sitting in the innermost parts of the cave. The comedy of the scene is exquisite: the king seeking the fugitive enters the very cave where the fugitive is hidden, for the most mundane of purposes. The cave is deep enough that the darkness conceals David's band from Saul's sight. Providence has placed them together in the most intimate possible proximity.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David's men whisper: 'Here is the day of which YHWH said to you, I will give your enemy into your hand, and you shall do to him as it seems good to you.' The men interpret the moment as divine fulfillment — an oracle apparently given earlier that David's enemy would be delivered to him. Their theological interpretation is not wrong (YHWH has brought Saul into the cave), but their conclusion — that David should now kill Saul — is wrong. Providence can create the opportunity without mandating the action.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David rises and cuts off a corner of Saul's robe (<em>kānāp</em>) secretly. The corner of the robe has covenant significance: the <em>kānāp</em> was the fringed hem that bore the owner's identity-seal in the ANE — like a signature. Grabbing or cutting the corner of a ruler's garment was a gesture with legal and covenant implications. David is claiming something — perhaps the kingdom itself — but still cannot bring himself to harm the man.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Afterward, David's heart struck him because he had cut off the corner of Saul's robe. He says: 'YHWH forbid that I should do this thing to my lord, YHWH's anointed, to put out my hand against him, seeing he is YHWH's anointed (<em>māšîaḥ YHWH</em>).' David's conscience (<em>wayyak lēḇ-dāwid ʾōṯô</em>) — literally, 'his heart struck him' — is pricked even by the robe-cutting. If cutting a garment corner troubles him, how much more the taking of life. The inviolability of the anointed is not a political calculation for David but a theological conviction.</p>",
    "7": "<p>David restrains his men with words and does not allow them to attack Saul. Saul leaves the cave and goes on his way. The contrast between David's restraint (against his own men's urging) and Saul's earlier inability to restrain himself (11:13 aside) is the chapter's moral argument. David's authority over his men is the authority of covenant principle over military opportunity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Afterward David rises and goes out of the cave and calls after Saul: 'My lord the king!' When Saul looks behind him, David bows with his face to the earth and pays homage. David's posture — bowing before the king he just had in his power — is the enacted argument of everything he will say. The physical deference demonstrates that the power relationship has not changed in David's mind; Saul is still the king and David is still the subject.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David addresses Saul: 'Why do you listen to people who say, David is seeking your harm? Behold, this day your eyes have seen how YHWH gave you today into my hand in the cave. Some said to kill you, but my eye had pity on you.' David frames the confrontation as an evidence-presentation: the robe corner he is about to produce is exhibit A in the argument that he had the opportunity to harm Saul and chose not to. He is also exposing Saul's advisors as the source of the paranoia.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I said I will not put out my hand against my lord, for he is YHWH's anointed.' The theological principle is given explicitly: the reason for restraint is not strategic (David doesn't want civil war), not psychological (David doesn't hate Saul yet), but covenantal — Saul is YHWH's anointed. As long as YHWH has designated Saul as king, David will not act against that designation by human force. The anointing creates an inviolability that supersedes David's own right of self-defense.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'See, my father, see the corner of your robe in my hand. For in that I cut off the corner of your robe and did not kill you, you may know and see that there is no wrong or treason in my hands.' David produces the evidence — the robe corner — and makes the inference explicit: if I were your enemy I would have killed you; I cut only your robe; therefore I am not your enemy. The word 'father' (<em>ʾāḇî</em>) is David's term of address for Saul — the covenant relationship of son to father-in-law is still claimed even in this confrontation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'YHWH judge between me and you; YHWH avenge me against you, but my hand shall not be against you.' The appeal to divine judgment rather than human vindication is the legal principle that governs David's behavior throughout the fugitive years: YHWH is the judge between the anointed who has been wronged and the anointed who has wronged him. David removes himself from the role of prosecutor, judge, and executioner — all of which he could legally claim — and assigns all three to YHWH.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'As the proverb of the ancients says, Out of the wicked comes wickedness. But my hand shall not be against you.' David cites a proverbial principle: evil actions flow from an evil character. The proverb is an implicit self-testimony: he has not acted wickedly, therefore (unlike Saul) he is not wicked. The appeal to proverbial wisdom grounds his self-defense in shared cultural understanding rather than merely personal claim.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'After whom has the king of Israel come out? After whom are you pursuing? A dead dog! A single flea!' David uses the self-deprecation of ANE diplomatic speech — presenting himself as insignificant — to highlight the absurdity of a royal army pursuing one man through the wilderness. 'A dead dog' and 'a single flea' are hyperboles of insignificance that reframe the pursuit as beneath royal dignity.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'YHWH will be judge and will decide between me and you. He will see, and he will plead my cause and deliver me from your hand.' The triple appeal — YHWH as judge, advocate (<em>rîḇ</em>), and deliverer — is a formal legal declaration. David is not merely expressing hope; he is filing a legal brief with the divine court. The rîḇ-vocabulary (lawsuit, to plead a cause) places the confrontation within the covenant lawsuit framework that Samuel had used in ch 12.</p>",
    "16": "<p>When David finishes, Saul says: 'Is this your voice, my son David?' And Saul weeps. The weeping is genuine — the narrative gives no indication of manipulation. Saul recognizes in David's restraint something he himself no longer possesses: covenant faithfulness to a rival. The address 'my son David' (<em>bənî dāwîḏ</em>) acknowledges the covenant relationship David has just claimed with his address of 'my father.'</p>",
    "17": "<p>Saul says: 'You are more righteous than I (<em>ṣaddîq ʾattāh mimmennî</em>), for you have repaid me good, whereas I have repaid you evil.' Saul's confession is the chapter's moral climax: the king who has been pursuing David with three thousand men acknowledges that David is in the right. The two terms <em>ṣaddîq</em> (righteous) and <em>rāʿ</em> (evil) are the covenant categories of those who keep faith and those who break it. Saul has just pronounced covenant judgment on himself.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'You have declared this day how you have dealt well with me, in that you did not kill me when YHWH put me into your hands.' Saul's acknowledgment is precise: YHWH had given Saul into David's hand — the opportunity was genuine and divinely arranged — and David chose not to use it. The theology of restraint is confirmed by the king himself.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'For if a man finds his enemy, will he let him go away safe? So may YHWH reward you with good for what you have done to me this day.' The rhetorical question identifies what David did as extraordinary: no one releases a captured enemy. The reward-prayer is Saul invoking YHWH's blessing on the man he has been trying to kill — a covenant contradiction Saul himself seems to sense.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'And now, behold, I know that you shall surely be king, and that the kingdom of Israel shall be established in your hand.' Saul's acknowledgment of David's future kingship is the definitive royal concession. It confirms what Jonathan, Samuel, and Abigail have all said. The irony is that Saul's own recognition of YHWH's purpose does not change his behavior: he will resume the pursuit in ch 26. Knowledge of divine will and submission to it can be permanently severed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Swear to me therefore by YHWH that you will not cut off my offspring after me, and that you will not destroy my name out of my father's house.' Saul's request reflects the ANE practice of new dynasties eliminating potential claimants from the previous dynasty. His request is essentially a dynastic-continuity oath — he is asking David to spare the family line even after taking the throne. The oath he asks for is entirely reasonable; ANE parallel examples abound.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David swears to Saul. Then Saul goes home and David and his men go up to the stronghold. The chapter ends in separation: the oath is sworn, the covenant gesture is complete, but the structural situation is unchanged. Saul returns to his palace; David returns to the wilderness. No political resolution has occurred, only a moral one. The pursuit will resume (ch 26), confirming that Saul's genuine moments of clarity cannot be sustained against the pressure of the evil spirit.</p>"
  }
}

